
* Motivation
- It is paramount that hardware designs are free from any bugs. Software engineers depend on the hardware to fullfill its
  functional contract. Unlike software it is impossible to fix a bug in hardware once that is sold. The bug may be very hard
  to detect and may even propogate and show up as software bugs perplexing software engineers
- How to we know that our design is free from bugs and works as we describe it to be?
  - Testing against a bunch of input/ouput combos to see that nothing fails
    - But this is only as good as our input/output coverage
    - Even for a uncomplicated module taking 2 64-bit values and producing a single 64-bit value, our test space will be
      ${{0, 1}^{64} \times {0, 1}^{64}} \times {0, 1}^{64}}
  - Formal Verification
    - Coming up with assertions is a non trivial task
    


* Questions
- If the data to fine tune a LLM for assertions is sparse can we try to transfer over knowledge from software formal verification
  if we have more data for that?
- If there are supposed bugs in the RTL code itself won't Goldmine produce wrong invariants? Because there seems to be no input
  about the design intent of the designer
- On the other hand how does not having access to the verilog code affect HARM? It is purely a blackbox solution.
- HARM doesn't use any formal verifier to verify its design? It ranks and filter using user defined metrics
- Both HARM and Goldmine are tested on small modules. They talked about global invariants but idk where they tested that. 
- In AssertionBench they trained on 10 assertions and tested on over 100 examples. I feel like that training amount was very very
  low considering that they themselves couldn't find assertions in the wild and had to generate them using GoldMine and HARM
- They didn't compare LLMs vs HARM or Goldmine. A test in which a LLM is trained on numerous assertions and given a new design how does
  it compare against Goldmine and HARM

